# Phase 3: AI Studio Integration

This phase focuses on the "Magic Moment" engine—automatically converting long-form videos into viral Shorts using Gemini 2.5 Flash and server-side video processing.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Gemini API Key**: To enable real AI analysis, I need a `GEMINI_API_KEY` added to [.env.local](file:///C:/GOLive/.env.local). If not provided, I will use a simulated high-fidelity mock.

> [!WARNING]
> **Resource Intensive**: Video clipping with `ffmpeg` can be CPU intensive. For this build, we will use `ffmpeg-static` to process clips on the server.

## Proposed Changes

### [Backend Components]

#### [NEW] [video-clipping.ts](file:///C:/GOLive/lib/video-clipping.ts)
A utility wrapper around `fluent-ffmpeg` that handles:
- Downloading raw video from R2.
- Trimming based on timestamps.
- Converting to 9:16 aspect ratio (blur-padding for horizontal videos).

#### [MODIFY] [analyze/route.ts](file:///C:/GOLive/app/api/ai-studio/analyze/route.ts)
Integrate `@google/genai` to:
- Pass video description/metadata to Gemini 2.5 Flash.
- Receive JSON-formatted timestamps for "viral moments".

#### [NEW] [clip/route.ts](file:///C:/GOLive/app/api/ai-studio/clip/route.ts)
A POST endpoint that:
- Triggers the clipping engine.
- Uploads the resulting `.mp4` to the `/shorts` folder in R2.
- Creates a new entry in the `videos` table with `is_short: true`.

### [Frontend Components]

#### [MODIFY] [page.tsx](file:///C:/GOLive/app/studio/ai-studio/page.tsx)
- Connect "Clip & Post" buttons to the `/api/ai-studio/clip` route.
- Add "Blur Padding" toggle for horizontal-to-vertical conversion.
- Implement real-time progress bars for the clipping process.

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
- `npm run dev` to verify the API responses.
- Check Supabase for new `is_short` records after clipping.

### Manual Verification
- Navigate to `/shorts` to verify the clipped video plays with correct snap-scrolling.
- Verify the video is correctly stored in Cloudflare R2 dashboard.
